M4 is the capstone evidence milestone — it must prove M1–M3 converged the trust model, composition authority, and export readiness as claimed, then add durable drift gates so those claims don't erode. The task explicitly asks to produce a final North Star proof mapping artifact and asks to strengthen (not build from scratch) gates that already have partial implementations from M1–M3. Root questions: (1) What is the current pass/fail baseline from clean checkout? (2) What gaps exist in the M1 trust-model gate after M2/M3 added new docs and surfaces? (3) Does the composition authority gate cover all migrated readiness consumers beyond the two files it currently monitors, and does a fixture exist proving legacy-only fields aren't authoritative post-projection? (4) Can every user-facing export blocker be traced back to a planner-owned RenderBlocker, or do legacy guard scans / route strings still bypass the planner? (5) After M1–M3 code changes, do the supported/deferred matrices still agree with reality, especially the D-020/B-002 entries that mark the render planner as deferred? (6) Which exact files/tests prove each of the 7 North Star required proof items?

## Research Areas

1. A1-quality-baseline: Determine the current pass/fail state of the quality:check pipeline (or the extension/trust/composition/export-relevant subset) from a clean checkout. Identify which checks already pass, which fail, and whether any failures are pre-existing (not introduced by M1–M3). This establishes the evidence baseline that all M4 gate-strengthening work starts from and the proof note references. Also confirm that test:extensions, test:readiness, and the quality:check aggregate command exist and are runnable.
2. A2-trust-gate-gaps: M1's check-trust-model-truth.mjs scans SDK, schema, ExtensionManager UI, docs/extensions, docs/video-editor, examples, and scripts/quality for forbidden trust claims (sandboxing, permission enforcement, marketplace safety, untrusted extension support, capability gates). M2 and M3 may have introduced new docs (e.g., shader-execution-model.md, composition-spine docs, planner/export docs) or new code paths that touch trust language but fall outside the gate's scan targets or rule patterns. Audit: (a) what surfaces were added/changed in M2–M3 that the gate doesn't scan, (b) whether the forbidden-term regex rules catch edge cases like 'permission enforcement' in composition/export contexts, (c) whether the denial/future-deferral context recognition correctly handles M2/M3's deferred-trust language. Produce a prioritized list of rule additions, scan-target expansions, and fixture gaps.
3. A3-composition-gate-gaps: M2's shaderRefAuthority.test.ts monitors only renderPlanner.ts and exportGuard.ts for forbidden legacy shader reads (clip.app?.shader, config.app?.shaderPostprocess, TimelineShaderMetadata, legacyTimelineShaderMetadata). Audit whether additional readiness-path consumers escape monitoring: renderRouter.ts reads from renderPlanner and could re-introduce legacy reads; useRenderState.ts calls exportGuard and planRender directly; routeScopeValidation.ts and the renderability module participate in the readiness chain. Also audit whether the North Star required fixture — 'legacy-only shader/ref fields do not count as authoritative after projection is disabled' — exists in compositionGraphProjector.test.ts (1835 lines) or needs a dedicated fixture. Identify forbidden-pattern gaps for reference-resolution legacy reads (contribution refs, effect/transition ID reads).
4. A4-export-blocker-trace: M3 claims every user-facing export/render blocked state derives from planner blockers. Trace the full chain end-to-end: user-facing blocked UI (useRenderState.ts → derived blocked/ready states → UI components) → scanExportConfig() or fast-path logic → planRender() → RenderBlocker objects. Identify every code path where: (a) a user-facing block message is sourced from a non-planner path (legacy export guard findings, direct route-string checks in getFastRenderRouteDecision, renderRouter decisions that don't go through planRender), (b) a planner blocker exists but is not surfaced to the user, or (c) the D-020 deferred entry ('Full render planner implementation') contradicts M3's 'planner-owned readiness' claim. Produce the inventory of gap locations where M4 must add or strengthen tests proving planner provenance.
